See the workflow module for more discussion about this specification that are typically involved in workflow.

Replaces portion of prior notion of 'instantiates'. Provides traceability of auto-creation.

GeneratedFrom is a specialized type of 'derived from'. The expectation is that the initial version of an artifact that was generatedFrom a definition will also complyWith that definition. However, it is possible that subsequent revisions may invalidate 'compliesWith'. Those revisions would not invalidate the 'generatedFrom' assertion.
Also see the [notes](workflow-extension.html#instantiation) in the workflow extensions area for more guidance on this element.

References a resource or provides a code or text that explains why this event occurred or request was created
Based on the [Event](event.html) and [Request](request.html) pattern reason elements
For free text (uncoded data) use reasonCode.text
Other information that may be relevant to this event.

Other resources *from the patient record* that may be relevant to the event. The information from these resources was either used to create the instance or is provided to help with its interpretation. This extension **should not** be used if more specific inline elements or extensions are available. For example, use `Observation.hasMember` instead of supportingInformation for representing the members of an Observation panel.
Based on the [Event](event.html) and [Request](request.html) pattern supportingInfo elements
Documentation or 'knowledge artifacts' relevant to the base resource such as citations, supporting evidence, documentation of processes, caveats around testing methodology.

Allows referencing the knowledge artifacts such as citations, supporting evidence, documentation of processes, caveats around testing methodology and other supporting documentation relevant to the 'parent' resource.
{This element isn't sufficiently common to be part of any pattern, but is potentially relevant as an extension for both request and event resources.}

Note that in contrast this extension, the [supportingInfo extension](extension-workflow-supportinginfo.html) references other resources *from the patient record* that were used in creating the resource.
Indicates that this event is relevant to the specified research study(ies).

Allows elements that are relevant to a research study to be linked to that study.
{This element isn't sufficiently common to be part of the core patterns for any resource, but it is potentially relevant to resources from both the [Event](event.html) and [Request](request.html) patterns.}

This relevance might mean that the even occurred as part of the study protocol, but can also include events that occurred outside the study but still have relevance (e.g. adverse events, co-occurring medications, unexpected Observations, etc.)
Identifies the episode(s) of care that this resource is relevant to. Establishes the EpisodeOfCare as a 'grouper' of resources that are relevant to that episode.

Links the {{title}} to the episode of care context.
{This element isn't sufficiently common to be part of the core patterns for any resource, but it is potentially relevant to resources from both the [Event](event.html) and [Request](request.html) patterns.}
Points to a preceding event within a workflow that was a prerequisite for or provides other justification for the current action.

Allows linking a previous action (whether successful or failure) whose existence helps to either justify or demonstrate the appropriateness of the current action. Possible examples:
* Pointing to a "first line" drug prescription when ordering a second-line drug. * Lodging a formal disagreement after the rejection of a request for correction. * Physiotherapy order referencing what therapy(ies) had already been done

This is distinct from 'reason'. The reason why the action is necessary is distinct from pointing to prerequisites or preceding workflow steps that allow or necessitate the current action. The prerequisites could be driven by a formal protocol (e.g. PlanDefinition), but that's not necessary for this to be relevant.
